msContents.summary: This is a mid-fourteenth-century French manuscript, which contains the text of Giles of Rome's De regimine principum, as well as a table of the chapters for Book II, part 2 through Book III, part 2 and the Office of Saint Catherine. There is one seven-line historiated pink initial on a blue background, with blue and red acanthus leaves extending along the inner margin, showing a three quarter portrait, possibly of the author, clad in his black Augustinian robes presenting a book. The initial and border decoration are badly worn. There are also two- to three-line red and blue ink initials with penwork flourishes in the other color marking major text divisions, running heads alternating red and blue letters, paragraph marks alternating red and blue, chapter headings in red, and guide letters for decorator visible. The ink has worn in places, and there is some water damage in the margins, but there is no loss of text due to this; however, the text is defective and breaks off or is missing portions with an entire quire missing from fols. 125-136, containing portions of Book II chapter 12 and all of chapters 1-6 and portions of chapter 7 of Book III.

msItem.title: De regimine principum
msItem.author: Giles, of Rome, Archbishop of Bourges, approximately 1243-1316

msItem.title: Preface to De regimine principum
msItem.incipit: Ex illustrissima ac sanctissima prosapia oriundo suo domino speciali. domino Philippo primogenito et heredi preclarissimi uiri domini Philippi dei gratia illustrissimi regis francorum... [fol. 1r]

msItem.title: Table of chapters, Bk. I, part 1: Incipiunt capitula prime partis libri primi
msItem.incipit: Quis sit modus procedendi in regimine principum [fol. 1v]

msItem.title: De regimine principum
msItem.incipit: Oportet ut latitudo sermonis in unaquaque re fit secundum exigenciam ipsius rei et non magis nec minus ut uult philosophus... [fol. 1v]
msItem.explicit: Quod totum ordinare debent ad commune bonum et ad pacem ciuium, nam si intendunt commune bonum et pacem ciuium merebuntur pacem illam eternam in qua suprema requies quam deus ipse suis promisit fidelibus qui est benedictus in secula seculorum. Amen. [fol. 174r]

msItem.title: Table of chapters, Book II, part 2 through Book III, part 2: Incipiunt Rubrice capitulorum secundae partis secundi libri de regimine principum
msItem.incipit: Quod decet omnes parentes circa proprios filios esse sollicitos [fol. 174r]
msItem.explicit: Expliciunt rubrice super libros de regimine principum [fol. 176v]

msItem.title: Office of Saint Catherine: Officium beate Katerine uirginis quod ordinauit dominus Johannes papa xxii...
msItem.incipit: Deprecare regem celi pro me uirgo Katerina/ adiuuare queso veni et saluare me festina [fol. 177v]
msItem.explicit: ...ad mortem quod Christus est peruenire ualeamus per dominum nostrum Jesum Christum. Amen. [fol. 178r]

supportDesc.extent: iii+178+iii; 261 x 194 mm bound to 274 x 205 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Early foliation in ink, upper left recto (1-194); modern refoliation in pencil, upper left recto

p.signatures: Some quire signatures in red ink, lower right recto

p.catchwords: Catchwords, enclosed in penwork rectangles, or in a few cases, in more elaborate penwork decorations, in lower margin at folios: 14v, 26v, 40v, 50v, 62v, 84v, 96v, 108v, 120v, 132v, 144v, 156v, 168v

layoutDesc.layout: Fols. 1r-176v: two columns, thirty-two lines, ruled with single vertical and horizontal bounding lines full across in ink; pricking visible in upper and lower margins; written area: 165 x 115 mm
Fols. 177v-178r: two columns, twenty-eight to thirty-five lines, with double vertical bounding lines; written area: 256 x 160 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: One seven-line historiated pink initial on blue background, with blue and red acanthus leaves extending along inner margin, showing a three quarter portrait, possibly of the author, clad in his black Augustinian robes presenting a book (fol. 1r); initial and border decoration badly worn; two-to three-line red and blue ink initials with penwork flourishes in the other color marking major text divisions; running heads alternate red and blue letters; paragraph marks alternating red and blue; chapter headings in red; guide letters for decorator visible
Inside front coverBookplate, Howard Lehman Goodhart
1rSeven-line inhabited initial E of a monk in a black habit, damaged

binding.p: Nineteenth-century quarter bound in blind-tooled brown calf over oak boards with two plaited leather fastenings of three strands each; gold tooled title on spine: "AEGIDIUS/ DE REG/ PRINCIPU"; at bottom "c. 1350"

history.provenance: Early provenance unknown; offered for sale by Maggs, Cat. 542 (1930) n. 73, with facs.; sold by Sotheby (London, 1934 March 12, n. 834) to Rowe; sold by Sotheby (London, 1934 Nov. 26, n. 520) to Howard L. Goodhart (bookplate), and presented by him to Bryn Mawr College, March 1949
